<subSubSection id="299D32DEFFA8C510FF0EFC2BB4A8FF2E" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" type="description">
<paragraph id="61386155FFA8C513FF0EFC2BB56AF9C7" blockId="1.[151,1437,998,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">
The species of the 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FEECFC2AB1F8F86D" box="[373,465,999,1024]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyptidis">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FEECFC2AB1F8F86D" box="[373,465,999,1024]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">hyptidis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group present unique characters within 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FC34FC2AB42AF86D" box="[941,1027,999,1024]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FC34FC2AB42AF86D" box="[941,1027,999,1024]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">Centris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, particularly in the morphology of the elaiospathes, which includes the extremely small posterior giant setae (secondary comb), apparently not used for oil collection, judging by their vestigial condition. This group of species presents interesting associations with oil-producing plants, mainly of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FC1DFB96B42AF819" box="[900,1027,1115,1140]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Angelonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FC1DFB96B42AF819" box="[900,1027,1115,1140]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">Angelonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FB8DFB97B4FCF819" box="[1044,1237,1114,1140]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Plantaginaceae</taxonomicName>
), which possess trichomatic elaiophores, which, unlike the epithelial elaiophores, require specialized structures for their exploitation (Vogel 
<number id="D74F7372FFA8C513FEE7FB65B195F8AF" box="[382,444,1192,1218]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="1974.0">1974</number>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFA8C513FE51FB65B2E7F8AF" author="Neff" box="[456,718,1192,1218]" pageId="1" pageNumber="43" refString="Neff, J. L. &amp; Simpson, B. B. (1981) Oil-collecting structures in the Anthophoridae (Hymenoptera): morphology, function and use in systematics. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 54, 95 - 123." type="journal article" year="1981">
Neff &amp; Simpson 
<number id="D74F7372FFA8C513FD09FB65B2E7F8AF" box="[656,718,1192,1218]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="1981.0">1981</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; Simpson 
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FCD1FB65B352F8AC" box="[840,891,1192,1217]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number id="D74F7372FFA8C513FC13FB65B3E0F8AF" box="[906,969,1192,1218]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="1990.0">1990</number>
). Due the positioning of the elaiophores in these plants, often arranged within a pair of sacks or cavities, they are accessible only to the first pair of legs of bees, which present the setae of the primary comb of the midlegs reduced or separated and, therefore, no longer used for the oil-collection (
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFA8C513FDE9FAD1B386F95B" author="Vogel" box="[624,943,1308,1334]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" refString="Vogel, S. &amp; Machado, I. C. (1991) Pollination of four sympatric species of Angelonia (Scrophulariaceae) by oil-collecting bees in NE, Brazil. Plant Systematics and Evolution, 178, 153 - 178." type="journal article" year="1991">
Vogel &amp; Machado 
<number id="D74F7372FFA8C513FCF6FAD1B386F95B" box="[879,943,1308,1334]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="1991.0">1991</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Such behavior, correlated with its morphofunctional complement, seems to be an apomorphy within Centridini (
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFA8C513FBDEFA8FB546F931" author="Vogel" box="[1095,1391,1346,1372]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" refString="Vogel, S. &amp; Machado, I. C. (1991) Pollination of four sympatric species of Angelonia (Scrophulariaceae) by oil-collecting bees in NE, Brazil. Plant Systematics and Evolution, 178, 153 - 178." type="journal article" year="1991">
Vogel &amp; Machado 
<number id="D74F7372FFA8C513FAB6FA8FB546F931" box="[1327,1391,1346,1372]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="1991.0">1991</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), in which females are basically equipped to oil-collection activity using fore and midlegs (
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFA8C513FB17FAA4B5BEF9EE" author="Neff" box="[1166,1431,1385,1411]" pageId="1" pageNumber="43" refString="Neff, J. L. &amp; Simpson, B. B. (1981) Oil-collecting structures in the Anthophoridae (Hymenoptera): morphology, function and use in systematics. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 54, 95 - 123." type="journal article" year="1981">
Neff &amp; Simpson 
<number id="D74F7372FFA8C513FAC0FAA4B5BEF9EE" box="[1369,1431,1385,1411]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="1981.0">1981</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFA8C513FF0EFA5DB19AF9C7" author="Vogel" box="[151,435,1424,1450]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" refString="Vogel, S. &amp; Machado, I. C. (1991) Pollination of four sympatric species of Angelonia (Scrophulariaceae) by oil-collecting bees in NE, Brazil. Plant Systematics and Evolution, 178, 153 - 178." type="journal article" year="1991">
Vogel &amp; Machado 
<number id="D74F7372FFA8C513FEECFA5DB19AF9C7" box="[373,435,1424,1450]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="1991.0">1991</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), with both pairs of legs possessing compact and well-developed setal combs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="61386155FFA8C513FF5CFA7BB2BEFAFF" blockId="1.[151,1437,998,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">
Given the location of the elaiophores in 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FD3AFA7BB37EF9BD" box="[675,855,1462,1488]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Plantaginaceae</taxonomicName>
, oil gathering is restricted to a limited number of visitors, which as in the case of the females of the 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FD76FA10B365F99B" box="[751,844,1501,1526]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyptidis">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FD76FA10B365F99B" box="[751,844,1501,1526]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">hyptidis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, possess their elaiospathes highly modified not only by the reduction of the secondary posterior setae but also by the presence of long and branched bristles of spatulate apex (
<figureCitation id="F9BC7DD0FFA8C513FE42F9E7B278FA29" box="[475,593,1578,1604]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="8.[151,272,1530,1554]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,506,1502]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,506,1503]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Centris thelyopsis n. sp., 9 – 10, female holotype, 11 – 12, male paratype. 9, Head, frontal view. 10, Habitus, lateral view. 11, Head, frontal view. 12, Habitus, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/187213/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">
Figures 
<number id="D74F7372FFA8C513FDDBF9E7B278FA29" box="[578,593,1578,1604]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
C and G in 
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFA8C513FD7BF9E7B424FA29" author="Vogel" box="[738,1037,1578,1604]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" refString="Vogel, S. &amp; Machado, I. C. (1991) Pollination of four sympatric species of Angelonia (Scrophulariaceae) by oil-collecting bees in NE, Brazil. Plant Systematics and Evolution, 178, 153 - 178." type="journal article" year="1991">
Vogel &amp; Machado 
<number id="D74F7372FFA8C513FC52F9E7B424FA29" box="[971,1037,1578,1604]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="1991.0">1991</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). These bristles are used for oilcollection not through scraping of the elaiophores as in other species of 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FB92F99CB44DFA07" box="[1035,1124,1617,1642]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FB92F99CB44DFA07" box="[1035,1124,1617,1642]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">Centris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but by absorption, using capillarity forces (
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFA8C513FEF2F9B5B2A3FAFF" author="Vogel" box="[363,650,1656,1682]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" refString="Vogel, S. &amp; Machado, I. C. (1991) Pollination of four sympatric species of Angelonia (Scrophulariaceae) by oil-collecting bees in NE, Brazil. Plant Systematics and Evolution, 178, 153 - 178." type="journal article" year="1991">
Vogel &amp; Machado 
<number id="D74F7372FFA8C513FDD2F9B5B2A3FAFF" box="[587,650,1656,1682]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="1991.0">1991</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="61386155FFA8C513FF5CF953B211FB17" blockId="1.[151,1437,998,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">
In the case of 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FEF6F952B204FAD5" box="[367,557,1695,1720]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyptidis">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FEF6F952B204FAD5" box="[367,557,1695,1720]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">Centris hyptidis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it is observed a significant reduction in the size of the setae forming the primary anterior comb, which remains almost hidden among the rest of the pilosity of the basitarsi. Fore legs of 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FF21F921B112FB68" box="[184,315,1772,1798]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyptidis">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FF21F921B0E2FB68" box="[184,203,1772,1797]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FF45F921B112FB68" box="[220,315,1772,1797]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">hyptidis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are disproportionately long, which allow access to elaiophores of e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FB0EF921B5BCFB68" box="[1175,1429,1772,1797]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Angelonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pubescens">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FB0EF921B5BCFB68" box="[1175,1429,1772,1797]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">Angelonia pubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is visited only for oil gathering, being in turn, its unique legitimate visitor (
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFA8C513FBF2F8DFB5A6FB41" author="Vogel" box="[1131,1423,1810,1836]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" refString="Vogel, S. &amp; Machado, I. C. (1991) Pollination of four sympatric species of Angelonia (Scrophulariaceae) by oil-collecting bees in NE, Brazil. Plant Systematics and Evolution, 178, 153 - 178." type="journal article" year="1991">
Vogel &amp; Machado 
<number id="D74F7372FFA8C513FAD6F8DFB5A6FB41" box="[1359,1423,1810,1836]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="1991.0">1991</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). On the other hand, females of 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FE6EF8F4B2F5FB3F" box="[503,732,1849,1874]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyptidoides">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FE6EF8F4B2F5FB3F" box="[503,732,1849,1874]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">Centris hyptidoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FC8DF8F4B383FB3F" box="[788,938,1849,1875]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thelyopsis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FC8DF8F4B30EFB3F" box="[788,807,1849,1874]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FCACF8F4B383FB3F" box="[821,938,1849,1874]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">thelyopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="48C0003CFFA8C513FC2BF8F5B3DDFB3F" box="[946,1012,1848,1874]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" rank="species">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFA8C513FC2BF8F5B3DDFB3F" bold="true" box="[946,1012,1848,1874]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
possess forelegs with normal length and the primary comb less reduced.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="61386155FFA8C510FF5CF84BB388FC92" blockId="1.[151,1437,998,2030]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,152,835]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">
Within Centridini, there is an ancestral relationship with plants with epithelial elaiophores, particularly with species of 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFA8C513FED5F860B1D5FBAA" box="[332,508,1965,1991]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Malpighiaceae</taxonomicName>
. Independent losses of the ability to collect oils, with a corresponding reduction or loss of the respective structures have been observed in several species-groups and subgenera (for example in 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FF2FFF55B2DBFCDF" authority="Toro &amp; Chiappa" authorityName="Toro &amp; Chiappa" box="[182,754,152,178]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moldenkei" subGenus="Wagenknechtia">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FF2FFF55B0F8FCDC" box="[182,209,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">C.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FF7DFF55B1B1FCDC" box="[228,408,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Wagenknechtia</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FE32FF55B20CFCDC" box="[427,549,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">moldenkei</emphasis>
Toro &amp; Chiappa
</taxonomicName>
, some species of 
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FC5CFF55B3C8FCDC" box="[965,993,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">C.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FC6AFF55B4AFFCDC" box="[1011,1158,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Penthemisia</emphasis>
) and species-groups in North and South American 
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FE74FF72B220FCB5" box="[493,521,191,216]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">C.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FD85FF72B284FCB5" box="[540,685,191,216]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Paracentris</emphasis>
)), along with a variety of modifications of the oil-collecting apparatuses, related with the radiation in the spectrum of oil hosts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="61386155FFABC510FF5CFEC1B4A8FF2E" blockId="2.[151,1437,152,835]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">
The species of the 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FE3FFEC1B22DFD48" box="[422,516,268,293]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyptidis">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FE3FFEC1B22DFD48" box="[422,516,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">hyptidis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group are associated with the diagonal of open dry areas, with 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FB65FEC1B554FD48" box="[1276,1405,268,293]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyptidis">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FB65FEC1B554FD48" box="[1276,1405,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">C. hyptidis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Caatinga (including peripheral areas in the upper Tocantins basin, in northeastern Goiás, 
<collectingCountry id="199021C5FFABC510FA83FEFFB543FD21" box="[1306,1386,306,332]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Brazil</collectingCountry>
), 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FA19FEFFB10BFD1F" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyptidoides">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FA19FEFFB10BFD1F" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">C. hyptidoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Chaco, and 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FD9EFE94B28AFD1F" box="[519,675,345,370]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thelyopsis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FD9EFE94B28AFD1F" box="[519,675,345,370]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">C. thelyopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="48C0003CFFABC510FD35FE95B2DBFD1F" box="[684,754,344,370]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" rank="species">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FD35FE95B2DBFD1F" bold="true" box="[684,754,344,370]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
in the dry forests of the upper Tocantins river (
<figureCitation id="F9BC7DD0FFABC510FAAAFE94B5A4FD1E" box="[1331,1421,345,371]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="9.[151,255,1348,1372]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,358,1316]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,351,1321]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 13. Distribution records for species of Centris of the hyptidis group." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/187214/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">
Fig. 
<number id="D74F7372FFABC510FAF5FE94B5A4FD1E" box="[1388,1421,345,371]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
). Several cases of bee groups with endemism in both the Chaco and Caatinga are well-known (
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FA9FFE4DB518FDF4" box="[1286,1329,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">e.g.</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFABC510FADBFE4DB0CAFDAD" author="Zanella" pageId="2" pageNumber="44" refString="Zanella, F. C. V. (2002 a) Systematics and biogeography of the bee genus Caenonomada Ashmead, 1899 (Hymenoptera: Apidae: Tapinotaspidini). Studies on Neotropical Fauna and Environment, 37, 249 - 261." type="journal article" year="2002" yearSuffix="a">
Zanella 
<number id="D74F7372FFABC510FF0EFE6BB0FFFDAD" box="[151,214,422,448]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" value="2002.0">2002</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFABC510FF69FE6BB1D9FDAD" author="Ramos" box="[240,496,422,448]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" refString="Ramos, K. S. &amp; Melo, G. A. R. (2007) Phylogeny and biogeography of bee genus Parapsaenythia (Apidae, Protandrenini) in the Chacoan subregion of South America. Darwiniana 45 (Suppl.): 117 - 119." type="journal article" year="2007">
Ramos &amp; Melo 
<number id="D74F7372FFABC510FE29FE6BB1D9FDAD" box="[432,496,422,448]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). None of these groups, however, contain species endemic to the dry forests of the valley of the Paranã river and slopes of the ‘Serra Geral’, in the upper Tocantins basin, in northeastern Goiás. Other bee species considered endemic to the Caatinga domain, 
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FC46FE39B420FE60" box="[991,1033,500,525]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">e.g.</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FB80FE39B540FE63" authority="Ducke" authorityName="Ducke" box="[1049,1385,500,526]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Arhysoceble" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huberi">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FB80FE39B529FE60" box="[1049,1280,500,525]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Arhysoceble huberi</emphasis>
(Ducke)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FF0EFDD7B260FE59" authority="Ducke" authorityName="Ducke" box="[151,585,538,564]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Caenonomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unicalcarata">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FF0EFDD7B1F6FE5E" box="[151,479,538,563]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Caenonomada unicalcarata</emphasis>
(Ducke)
</taxonomicName>
, or to smaller areas within it, e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FC42FDD7B570FE59" authority="Camargo" authorityName="Camargo" box="[987,1369,538,564]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Camargoia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nordestina">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FC42FDD7B4CAFE5E" box="[987,1251,538,563]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Camargoia nordestina</emphasis>
Camargo
</taxonomicName>
, have also been collected at the 
<typeStatus id="BE3CDFF7FFABC510FE4CFD8CB220FE36" box="[469,521,577,603]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FD0EFD8CB31FFE37" box="[663,822,577,602]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thelyopsis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FD0EFD8CB31FFE37" box="[663,822,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">C. thelyopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="48C0003CFFABC510FCA7FD8DB3AAFE37" box="[830,899,576,602]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" rank="species">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FCA7FD8DB3AAFE37" bold="true" box="[830,899,576,602]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
in the Paranã valley (G. Melo &amp; A. Aguiar, unpublished data). 
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFABC510FEE1FDA5B222FEEF" author="Silva" box="[376,523,616,642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" refString="Silva, J. M. C. (1997) Endemic bird species and conservation in the Cerrado Region, South America. Biodiversity and Conservation, 6, 435 - 450." type="journal article" year="1997">
Silva (
<number id="D74F7372FFABC510FE5CFDA5B22BFEEF" box="[453,514,616,642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" value="1997.0">1997</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFABC510FDDDFDA5B37CFEEF" author="Silva" box="[580,853,616,642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" refString="Silva, J. M. C. &amp; Bates, J. M. (2002) Biogeographic patterns and conservation in the South American Cerrado: a tropical savanna hotspot. BioScience, 52, 225 - 233." type="journal article" year="2002">
Silva and Bates (
<number id="D74F7372FFABC510FC94FDA5B364FEEF" box="[781,845,616,642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" value="2002.0">2002</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, in studies of bird distribution patterns within the Brazilian Cerrado, have recognized the Paranã valley as an area of endemism, based on the distribution of the two bird species, 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FEF2FD78B33AFEA2" authority="Snethlage" authorityName="Snethlage" box="[363,787,693,719]" class="Aves" family="Tyrannidae" genus="Knipolegus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="franciscanus">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FEF2FD78B2BCFEA3" box="[363,661,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Knipolegus franciscanus</emphasis>
Snethlage
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FCBAFD78B384FEA2" box="[803,941,693,719]" class="Aves" family="Tyrannidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Tyrannidae</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FC68FD78B5B5FEA2" authority="Miranda-Ribeiro" authorityName="Miranda-Ribeiro" box="[1009,1436,693,719]" class="Aves" family="Psittacidae" genus="Pyrrhura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Psittaciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pfrimeri">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FC68FD78B4E2FEA3" box="[1009,1227,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Pyrrhura pfrimeri</emphasis>
Miranda-Ribeiro
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FF06FD11B10CFE9B" box="[159,293,732,758]" class="Aves" family="Psittacidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Psittaciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Psittacidae</taxonomicName>
). The first bird species is also found in the dry forests of the middle São Francisco valley, in Bahia and northern Minas Gerais (
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFABC510FE44FCCFB2E9FF71" author="Silva" box="[477,704,770,796]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="44" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" refString="Silva, J. M. C. &amp; Oren, D. C. (1992) Notes on Knipolegus franciscanus Snethlage, 1928 (Aves: Tyrannidae), an endemism of central Brazilian dry forests. Goeldiana Zoologia, 16, 1 - 9." type="journal article" year="1992">
Silva &amp; Oren 
<number id="D74F7372FFABC510FD18FCCFB2E9FF71" box="[641,704,770,796]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" value="1992.0">1992</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), and therefore, has a distribution pattern comparable to that of 
<taxonomicName id="A6871AD6FFABC510FF0EFCE4B13FFF2F" box="[151,278,809,834]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyptidis">
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FF0EFCE4B13FFF2F" box="[151,278,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">C. hyptidis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, while the psittacid is restricted to northeastern Goiás (
<bibRefCitation id="05161CA4FFABC510FC05FCE4B45DFF2E" author="Olmos" box="[924,1140,809,835]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" refString="Olmos, F., Martuscelli, P. &amp; Silva e Silva, R. (1997) Distribution and dry-season ecology of Pfrimer's conure Pyrrhura pfrimeri, with a reappraisal of Brazilian Pyrrhura &quot; leucotis &quot;. Ornitologia Neotropical, 8, 121 - 132." type="journal article" year="1997">
Olmos 
<emphasis id="53F3BD47FFABC510FC6AFCE4B407FF2F" box="[1011,1070,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">et al.</emphasis>
<number id="D74F7372FFABC510FBACFCE4B45DFF2E" box="[1077,1140,809,835]" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
